00:45:18.750 --> 00:45:21.500
AUDIENCE: How do you
come up with swear words,

00:45:21.500 --> 00:45:23.574
or cursor words, dirty
words, or whatever.

00:45:23.574 --> 00:45:24.990
DAVID PETERSON:
There was actually

00:45:24.990 --> 00:45:28.510
a really interesting
book that came out

00:45:28.510 --> 00:45:32.820
just a couple years ago about
curse words in languages.

00:45:32.820 --> 00:45:33.819
There are patterns.

00:45:33.819 --> 00:45:34.610
There are patterns.

00:45:34.610 --> 00:45:37.480
Like all languages
have a feces word.

00:45:37.480 --> 00:45:39.330
All languages have
one of those, and it

00:45:39.330 --> 00:45:40.550
tends to be a curse word.

00:45:40.550 --> 00:45:46.260
But then also
things will differ.

00:45:46.260 --> 00:45:51.870
In French, for example, a lot
of swearing is with the devil.

00:45:51.870 --> 00:45:53.730
We don't tend to
do that as much,

00:45:53.730 --> 00:45:55.680
like say oh devil take you.

00:45:55.680 --> 00:45:58.300
It sounds a little fanciful,
but it doesn't actually

00:45:58.300 --> 00:46:00.950
feel like a swear.

00:46:00.950 --> 00:46:04.670
There are usual domains
that swear words come from.

00:46:04.670 --> 00:46:07.910
One of them is body functions.

00:46:07.910 --> 00:46:11.340
Another is reproduction,
and then another

00:46:11.340 --> 00:46:19.040
is usually religo-metaphorical
superstition type things.

00:46:19.040 --> 00:46:22.665
So all of my languages,
they all have a feces word

00:46:22.665 --> 00:46:25.040
because it seems like every
single language on the planet

00:46:25.040 --> 00:46:28.450
is always going to
have a feces word.

00:46:28.450 --> 00:46:31.600
But then with the
Dothraki, for example,

00:46:31.600 --> 00:46:34.590
since they place so
much cultural importance

00:46:34.590 --> 00:46:36.664
on being able to ride
and being able ride well,

00:46:36.664 --> 00:46:38.580
I guess if you can't
ride, they literally just

00:46:38.580 --> 00:46:42.090
abandon you and leave you to
die, which seems kind of weird.

00:46:42.090 --> 00:46:42.670
I don't know.

00:46:42.670 --> 00:46:43.211
I don't know.

00:46:43.211 --> 00:46:44.510
Seems cruel.

00:46:44.510 --> 00:46:45.780
I wouldn't do it.

00:46:45.780 --> 00:46:49.150
Look, if you were khalasar,
I wouldn't leave you behind.

00:46:49.150 --> 00:46:52.650
I'd find a cart for you.

00:46:52.650 --> 00:46:55.670
So we already had them
insulting Viserys calling him

00:46:55.670 --> 00:46:57.400
the cart king,
the sorefoot king,

00:46:57.400 --> 00:46:58.980
so it seemed like
calling somebody

00:46:58.980 --> 00:47:01.610
a walker would be
that type of insult

00:47:01.610 --> 00:47:04.354
where it kind of means
gringo when you're talking

00:47:04.354 --> 00:47:05.770
about somebody
who's non-Dothraki.

00:47:05.770 --> 00:47:08.190
If you're talking to a
Dothraki and you're joking,

00:47:08.190 --> 00:47:09.697
maybe you can get away with it.

00:47:09.697 --> 00:47:12.030
But if you're serious, you
could really insult somebody,

00:47:12.030 --> 00:47:12.720
you know?

00:47:12.720 --> 00:47:16.100
So I kind of went
there for that.

00:47:16.100 --> 00:47:19.710
And then otherwise
it's just fun stuff.

00:47:19.710 --> 00:47:24.542
With the "Defiance"
languages where

00:47:24.542 --> 00:47:26.250
you have all these
different alien races,

00:47:26.250 --> 00:47:27.624
and then they're
coming to Earth,

00:47:27.624 --> 00:47:31.170
there are actually a lot of
insults that go back and forth

00:47:31.170 --> 00:47:34.330
and change meanings
coming from English

00:47:34.330 --> 00:47:36.660
and then also coming
from the alien languages.

00:47:36.660 --> 00:47:39.147
And there's also
a lot of-- I don't

00:47:39.147 --> 00:47:41.480
know if you'd call it species
tension or racial tension,

00:47:41.480 --> 00:47:42.855
but there are a
lot of those type

00:47:42.855 --> 00:47:45.470
of terms that end
up getting used.

00:47:45.470 --> 00:47:49.030
It kind of depends on
the project, I guess.

00:47:49.030 --> 00:47:52.330
AUDIENCE: You started going this
direction in the last question,

00:47:52.330 --> 00:47:55.200
but I wanted to
ask, for Dothraki,

00:47:55.200 --> 00:47:57.620
in what way did
things like irregulars

00:47:57.620 --> 00:48:02.690
and the sort of sound of words
get influenced by the lifestyle

00:48:02.690 --> 00:48:05.350
and sort of character
of Dothraki?

00:48:05.350 --> 00:48:08.220
Like angry invectives
shouted from horse to horse,

00:48:08.220 --> 00:48:11.340
or communicating from horse
to horse, when you're writing.

00:48:11.340 --> 00:48:12.920
Can't really be a
delicate, difficult

00:48:12.920 --> 00:48:14.902
to understand language.

00:48:14.902 --> 00:48:16.110
DAVID PETERSON: I don't know.

00:48:16.110 --> 00:48:17.480
They do a lot of sitting too.

00:48:17.480 --> 00:48:19.510
And also if you notice--
and I did actually

00:48:19.510 --> 00:48:21.260
like this about how
they portrayed it--

00:48:21.260 --> 00:48:25.190
they show them in their
nomadic lifestyle.

00:48:25.190 --> 00:48:26.970
They show them moving
from place to place.

00:48:26.970 --> 00:48:28.970
And you'll notice that
when they move as a herd,

00:48:28.970 --> 00:48:30.960
it's very, very slowly.

00:48:30.960 --> 00:48:33.190
So it's not it's not a
quick thing that happens.

00:48:33.190 --> 00:48:35.860
So I figure a lot of
conversation happens.

00:48:35.860 --> 00:48:37.900
It's not that bad.

00:48:37.900 --> 00:48:39.360
It shouldn't be too loud.

00:48:41.960 --> 00:48:44.680
I don't know how much
that influenced--

00:48:44.680 --> 00:48:46.760
don't think that type of
thing really influences,

00:48:46.760 --> 00:48:50.332
say, the sound of the language
or the grammar a whole lot.

00:48:50.332 --> 00:48:51.790
I don't think that's
something that

00:48:51.790 --> 00:48:55.070
happens in natural
languages at least,

00:48:55.070 --> 00:48:56.760
and I was going for natural.

00:48:56.760 --> 00:49:00.170
As far as irregulars, that could
be an entirely different talk,

00:49:00.170 --> 00:49:05.420
but the process is that
for all the languages

00:49:05.420 --> 00:49:08.280
that I create I start
with a very old language,

00:49:08.280 --> 00:49:10.500
and then I evolve
the sound system.

00:49:10.500 --> 00:49:14.330
I evolve the word
meanings, and I

00:49:14.330 --> 00:49:18.300
evolve the grammar over a period
of between 1000 and 2000 years

00:49:18.300 --> 00:49:20.050
depending on what
the time frame is.

00:49:20.050 --> 00:49:25.100
And so things like irregular
conjugations, irregular

00:49:25.100 --> 00:49:28.860
declensions, irregular plurals--
if a language has irregular

00:49:28.860 --> 00:49:30.550
plurals, and all languages do.

00:49:30.550 --> 00:49:34.880
Those always come from basically
a combination of sound change

00:49:34.880 --> 00:49:37.320
and analogical change
and things like that.

00:49:37.320 --> 00:49:41.010
So for example, your
mouse, mice in English--

00:49:41.010 --> 00:49:44.440
that actually came from a
totally regular pluralization

00:49:44.440 --> 00:49:46.150
strategy where the
old word for mouse

00:49:46.150 --> 00:49:49.580
was "moos" with the long
"oo," and the regular plural

00:49:49.580 --> 00:49:51.320
was "moosi."

00:49:51.320 --> 00:49:54.320
And then what happened is that
the vowels changed, so "moos"

00:49:54.320 --> 00:49:56.920
eventually became mouse
in the great vowel shift.

00:49:56.920 --> 00:50:01.760
And then over on the right
hand, "moosi" became "mewsi."

00:50:01.760 --> 00:50:05.510
And then we lost that "ew"
vowel and it became "meesi."

00:50:05.510 --> 00:50:10.790
We lost the vowel on the end,
and then long E became I,

00:50:10.790 --> 00:50:12.870
and so then we're
left with mouse, mice.

00:50:12.870 --> 00:50:15.974
That's how irregularities
emerge in language.

00:50:15.974 --> 00:50:17.640
As a language creator,
it's challenging,

00:50:17.640 --> 00:50:20.490
but that's what you have to
try to emulate, that process.

00:50:20.490 --> 00:50:22.420
So that's where all the
irregulars come from.

00:50:22.420 --> 00:50:23.265
It's fun.

00:50:23.265 --> 00:50:25.890
AUDIENCE: One the languages that
you have mentioned in passing,

00:50:25.890 --> 00:50:30.000
but didn't say much
about, was the prosody.

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:32.730
What do you do come
up with that scheme?

00:50:32.730 --> 00:50:35.237
That's important for actors
delivering it for sure.

00:50:35.237 --> 00:50:37.070
DAVID PETERSON: I
actually realized too late

00:50:37.070 --> 00:50:38.528
I should've done
something on that.

00:50:38.528 --> 00:50:44.090
So first, if a language
is going to have stress,

00:50:44.090 --> 00:50:47.310
that's something that you can
just plan out and figure out--

00:50:47.310 --> 00:50:48.260
the stress system.

00:50:48.260 --> 00:50:53.800
I haven't been courageous
enough to try a tonal system

00:50:53.800 --> 00:50:58.674
with actors, because
with tonal systems

00:50:58.674 --> 00:51:00.340
it's so important to
get the tone right.

00:51:00.340 --> 00:51:02.672
It could be a change
in word meaning.

00:51:02.672 --> 00:51:04.130
I just don't feel
confident that it

00:51:04.130 --> 00:51:06.410
would come across
the correct way.

00:51:09.540 --> 00:51:11.120
If I was going to
be in a situation

00:51:11.120 --> 00:51:13.300
where I could be on
set every single day,

00:51:13.300 --> 00:51:14.870
and be there for
every single line,

00:51:14.870 --> 00:51:17.170
and say no that
was wrong, maybe.

00:51:17.170 --> 00:51:20.060
But I think actors would
really get tired of that.

00:51:20.060 --> 00:51:22.740
So I've only done
stress systems.

00:51:22.740 --> 00:51:27.720
And so stress systems, they come
up in a very-- stress systems

00:51:27.720 --> 00:51:29.700
work in a number
of ways basically.

00:51:29.700 --> 00:51:33.720
Some of it is based
on sound changes.

00:51:33.720 --> 00:51:36.769
So for example, the reason that
French apparently has no stress

00:51:36.769 --> 00:51:38.310
is because it's
lopped off everything

00:51:38.310 --> 00:51:41.600
off the ends of words, and so
the only kind of stress that's

00:51:41.600 --> 00:51:44.930
there is kind of a light
stress at the end of a word.

00:51:44.930 --> 00:51:50.210
But with Dothraki, for
example, the stress system

00:51:50.210 --> 00:51:51.192
is fairly simple.

00:51:51.192 --> 00:51:52.900
If it ends in a
consonant, it will always

00:51:52.900 --> 00:51:54.570
be stressed on
the last syllable.

00:51:54.570 --> 00:51:56.990
If ends in a vowel, it
will most of the time

00:51:56.990 --> 00:51:59.180
be stressed on the
first syllable,

00:51:59.180 --> 00:52:02.130
unless the second to
last syllable is heavy,

00:52:02.130 --> 00:52:03.190
then the stress is there.

00:52:08.290 --> 00:52:15.360
A nice example is like to
the Dothraki, dothrakaan,

00:52:15.360 --> 00:52:17.370
stressed on the last syllable.

00:52:17.370 --> 00:52:19.330
The proper pronunciation
of Dothraki

00:52:19.330 --> 00:52:21.690
is Dothraki, stress
on the first syllable.

00:52:21.690 --> 00:52:25.260
But the word for dragon,
"zhavvorsa," because there's

00:52:25.260 --> 00:52:29.010
that heavy internal syllable,
so it gets penultimate stress.

00:52:29.010 --> 00:52:32.250
Then there are a couple
of other strange things,

00:52:32.250 --> 00:52:34.409
like there are certain
derivation patterns that

00:52:34.409 --> 00:52:35.950
move the stress
around, but you don't

00:52:35.950 --> 00:52:38.670
need to worry about those.

00:52:38.670 --> 00:52:40.040
So that's the stress pattern.

00:52:40.040 --> 00:52:41.820
Then when it comes
to the intonation,

00:52:41.820 --> 00:52:44.450
that really is just
up to me to figure out

00:52:44.450 --> 00:52:47.380
how I want the intonation
of a sentence to go.

00:52:47.380 --> 00:52:52.370
And I am not happy with
any method of transcribing

00:52:52.370 --> 00:52:56.220
intonation that's ever been
devised in linguistics or out

00:52:56.220 --> 00:52:56.920
of linguistics.

00:52:56.920 --> 00:52:59.420
I really don't think that
there's a good way to do it.

00:52:59.420 --> 00:53:03.490
So all I do is just first I
record every sentence exactly

00:53:03.490 --> 00:53:05.510
the way it should
be spoken and hope

00:53:05.510 --> 00:53:07.610
that the actors will mimic.

00:53:07.610 --> 00:53:09.800
And then I kind of
do a thing where

00:53:09.800 --> 00:53:11.370
I do a phonetic breakdown.

00:53:11.370 --> 00:53:13.130
I don't do IPA
because I discovered

00:53:13.130 --> 00:53:17.780
actors don't learn that
anymore, which is too bad.

00:53:17.780 --> 00:53:19.870
I break it down
syllable by syllable,

00:53:19.870 --> 00:53:22.890
and I put syllables
that are supposed

00:53:22.890 --> 00:53:26.730
to have more
prominence in all caps.

00:53:26.730 --> 00:53:29.100
And so for languages
like Irathient

00:53:29.100 --> 00:53:33.090
on "Defiance" that have a really
funky intonational pattern,

00:53:33.090 --> 00:53:36.440
there are often words
were the entire word

00:53:36.440 --> 00:53:40.780
has high intonation, because
one of the neat things

00:53:40.780 --> 00:53:43.390
that Irathient does is for
its subordinate clauses, which

00:53:43.390 --> 00:53:45.380
usually come first,
most of the words

00:53:45.380 --> 00:53:47.130
actually get kind
of a high tone.

00:53:47.130 --> 00:53:48.850
And then we have the
comma, it goes down

00:53:48.850 --> 00:53:51.440
to the regular low tone.

00:53:51.440 --> 00:53:54.145
But again, this
is not something--

00:53:54.145 --> 00:53:56.270
I don't think it could be
written down effectively.

00:53:56.270 --> 00:54:01.120
I don't think it could
be conveyed effectively.

00:54:01.120 --> 00:54:04.830
So I really just do that with
the caps and the lowercase.

00:54:04.830 --> 00:54:06.407
I record all the
lines, and I just

00:54:06.407 --> 00:54:07.740
say, well, if it works it works.

00:54:07.740 --> 00:54:09.420
If it doesn't, if doesn't.

00:54:09.420 --> 00:54:11.470
Most of the time it works.

00:54:11.470 --> 00:54:14.120
I've noticed that to the
intonation that I do,

00:54:14.120 --> 00:54:16.560
they tend to do a more
subtle version, especially

00:54:16.560 --> 00:54:18.780
with Irathient, but
you can still hear it.

00:54:18.780 --> 00:54:21.170
And I think that actually
makes it a little better.

00:54:21.170 --> 00:54:22.820
Probably my thing
is to exaggerated,

00:54:22.820 --> 00:54:26.870
but at least it gives them the
idea of how it should sound.

00:54:26.870 --> 00:54:28.870
AUDIENCE: On that note,
join me in thanking him.

00:54:28.870 --> 00:54:29.828
DAVID PETERSON: Thanks.

00:54:29.828 --> 00:54:31.020
[APPLAUSE]

